	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Comprehensive Druid Guide, 1-19</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:cruelosdimera@aol.com">Demoree (Keith West)</a> | 
		            1/15/2001 2:36:58 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">A few things must be said about druids and the druid lifestyle at the outset. I hope that the reader will bear these in mind even before having created a druid, because as most of us know, there is no worse feeling than having to delete weeks of hard work just because of an attribute or race blunder. You need to understand that everything I say is taken from the perspective of a seventeenth level druid. I haven't been to the planes, I haven't stood toe to toe with Nagafen or Vox, and I haven't made my first million teleporting people the world over. So please, spare me the &quot;guides should only be written by people at x level or higher&quot; comments. This is just my advice, so take it with a grain of salt. Also, understand that I have played a few other classes (though the druid is the highest I have) and that I do have a fair understanding of how things work in Norrath. Finally, in everything I say, remember that there are more factors to success than being a druid at the specified level. Equipment does matter, as do buffs and general constitution. Please skim through the whole guide before taking anything for granted. But now I'm rambling, so onward.<BR>
<BR>
The first order of business is race. You have options of course, and I try not to be biased in my recommendations. Statistically speaking, halfling and wood elf are the definite choices. The lowered experience penalty makes halfling an excellent choice, and if you're big on the numbers game, you probably will be set on halfling immediately. I, however, was not. My brother refers to halflings, dwarves, and gnomes as social rejects, and though I don't necessarily agree with that, I am not familiar with Rivervale and Misty Thicket, and am somewhat familiar with the Greater Faydark. So I chose a wood elf, and have never for one moment regreted it. The other available classes should not be shunned, though. They suffer statistically, but the Qeynos area is an excellent starting place, and if you're set on not travelling until you can teleport (it can be done), you're wise to choose Qeynos as home.<BR>
<BR>
Class... is there really any question here? If you're not sure, read the title and the first two paragraphs a few more times and we'll see if we can all get on the same page here.<BR>
<BR>
Attribute allotment is relatively inflexible. Halflings will be better at melee early on, so putting more points into their melee attributes (strength, dexterity, or agility) is a viable option, but it is common knowledge that a high level druid (30's) enters melee either only when he/she has no mana, no SoW (or a mob [mob: mobile enemy, for those of you who really don't know] faster than SoW), and no friends; or when he/she's feeling macho or suicidal. Face it, you're a caster. Maybe not a pure one, but close enough to know when to put away the scimitar and lay on the fire. As such, it is extremely highly recommended that you pump attribute points into Wisdom until it won't take any more. Then have a look at what the attribute points do (should be a chart on Everlore somewhere) and use your own discretion to distribute what's left. Also consider that the most notable differences in point allotment come in multiples of five (i.e., if you have one at 74, 79, etc., put one more in it to bump it to the next level). To be perfectly honest, these last five points aren't going to kill you, so don't panic trying to decide what to do with them.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, pick a face, pick a name, pick a deity, pick a city (you won't have a choice in most cases).<BR>
<BR>
I'll be taking the perspective of the Kelethin druid for early on. Anyone who is having trouble wherever you are is welcome to try and get a teleport and bind over to keep up, but it's really not that big a deal. Mobs are generally the same the world over, and anything I mention here can be translated for another zone if you know the equivalents. If nothing else, just ask somebody.<BR>
<BR>
A few things to note about Kelethin, though:<BR>
Three lifts, PoD lift, Newbie lift, Orc Lift. The Pod lift is to the right of the newbie lift. To get to the orc lift on the ground, stand on the PoD lift and face the Priest of Discord (hence the name) and walk forward along the corner where the hill begins. Keep walking and you'll come up behind the Orc Lift. To get to the bank, go up the PoD lift and head straight across the bridge past the two merchants. Then turn left and go up the ramp. Voila. From the bank head left and down two stories to get to your guild. Kelethin is a pain to maneuver for a beginner.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Level 1<BR>
________________________<BR>
In a word, bats. Yes, bats. And bats alone. At level one you hunt bats. Got it? I cannot tell you just how important it is that you hunt specifically bats. Why? Wings. The only other reasonable option is decaying skeletons. You should spend your &quot;newbie&quot; [I hate that word] levels gaining experience and, more importantly, collecting bat wings and bone chips, as well as the occasional rusty weapon. Remember, a skeleton with a weapon supersedes any other option of enemy at this point, so if you see a dead guy waving an axe, go hurt him. Do not waste your time on bees. The point of all this bat and skeleton killing is for their loot. Whenever you acquire 20 bone chips or bat wings (hereafter referred to as a stack), auction them (i.e. /auction Selling stack of bat wings). High level casters will pay considerably for bat wings to use for levitation and other ...things, and necros are always in need of bone chips for conjuration, among other things. On the Innoruuk server I received as much as 20 platinum pieces for one stack of bat wings (although you should be happy if you can get as much as 10 for one).<BR>
<BR>
Purchase your remaining first level spells whenever possible. My advice: buy them all. Some will say that you should only purchase certain ones, but the truth of the matter is that there is enough money available through a little hard work to have them all. The most important spell you'll acquire is Snare, however, so if you are short on money early on, for whatever reason, make sure you get it at least. From this point on, I'm going to take it for granted that you did whatever was necessary to purchase the line of spells available at each spell level before throwing yourself back into the fray.<BR>
<BR>
Level 2-4<BR>
________________________<BR>
At these levels you also need to get into the habit of practicing three things: Sense heading, Forage (if you have it), and consider. No, consider is not a skill, but you need to make a habit of con'ing everything before you even think about attacking it. You'll see why in a moment. Set Forage and Sense Heading as hot keys and keep them in use all the time. This makes a world of difference later.<BR>
<BR>
By level 2, 3, or 4, orc pawns (or gnoll pups, whichever may be the case) will be blue to you, so kill them. Make sure to con them ahead of time; all orcs are not created equal. Also be sure to find them alone. Nothing worse than pulling an orc pawn only to have his buddy the oracle come running to his aid. Also, keep abreast of quests for this level (just check the Quest section on Everlore with your current zone); there are at least two or three you can accomplish in your spare time for fair experience and items/money.<BR>
<BR>
Keep an ear out for donations. Anybody giving away free stuff is to be met with the most pitiful expression possible. Yes, it's low, but take all of whatever equipment you have and stuff it away in your inventory or a bank. Also, if you did well selling bat wings, you might consider making some purchases if the deal's good.<BR>
<BR>
Level 5-6<BR>
________________________<BR>
At level five you get spells, buy them.<BR>
<BR>
At this point you can hunt (read: SOLO) orc centurions. The best way to go about this is to head to the orc lift and go straight down the path to orc hill. When the huts are in sight, camoflage yourself and go up the hill. At the top of the hill, turn right ninety degrees and head down the slope. You'll see two sets of huts on the ground below. Go past them a few feet, stop, turn around, camp. Harmony whichever orcs you don't want to pull (usually the ones that are higher than you: red or yellow) and then snare the one you want. If he gets close and you need to get away, root him and back off, then nuke. Take advantage of root while you have it, because these early levels are the only ones in which it's actually effective. By this method you can make it up to level 7 rather easily.<BR>
<BR>
Level 7-8<BR>
________________________<BR>
Level 7 and 8 are not mechanically, or technically, hell levels. But you might think they are anyway. I died a great many times at 7, and you will probably die at least once or twice. The problem arises when you discover how massive your down time is (since you don't have meditate yet) and how little experience these orcs are bringing now. There is a nice place to camp to wait out the misery though. Camo, then head into CB (just head past the two camping huts to the path and turn; you should be able to see the torches at the entrance). Walk past the entrance a little bit, then turn left and walk to the edge of the river running along the side. Across the river is a pair of orcs. One should be green, and the other is probably blue. Snare him, then nuke him until he dies. The effect is very similar to kiting, which is how you'll spend a great many hours once you hit 14, so get used to it. It's a wonderful feeling, watching the poor centurion truck his heavy tail all the way down to the bridge to get across while you nuke him. Once done, Camo again, sit down, and wait for the next spawn. This will get you to eight at least, wherein you should go practice in meditation (one point) to get it started. The orc will eventually go green, at which point you should more or less wander around near the entrance of CB (either inside or out) and kill orcs until you hit level nine. You may also want to begin dealing in &quot;orc belts&quot; and &quot;lego pads.&quot; These are essentially just quest items in Kaladim, but there's usually a good market for them in the Greater Faydark, so if you happen to get any, sell them for around 1 plat a piece and consider going back for more. Some people will tell you to work on getting a high AC, but considering that once you hit 14 you won't be taking damage much more except in emergency, I would suggest that you look for stat boosting items. not necessarily wisdom, but anything that seems like a bargain. 10, all of my attributes were green except for Charisma, and it makes a considerable difference. So be prepared to swindle people when the time comes, and know the market when it comes to equipment.<BR>
<BR>
Level 9<BR>
________________________<BR>
Spells, yay. At level nine, it's time to begin travelling. Granted, you could hang around the orc hill looking for the occasional blue to spawn, or you could go into CB and try to solo without starting a train ... or if you're really desperate, you could even group. Best bet, though, head to Butcherblock Mountains. Facing the CB entrance, turn left and follow the wall until the next zone. That's BB. Once you zone, follow the path until you find a guard um . . . shack, with two dwarfs and Mr. Bloodforge (can never remember his first name). If you're lucky, they'll all be dead and you can loot a Bloodforge Hammer and a few Dwarven Axes (they sell relatively well). But don't count on it. At this point, run around a bit and familiarize yourself with the area, so you'll know how to get back to those guards if you get desperate. Giant scarabs, dwarf skeletons, and goblins make for good experience here. Just make sure to con and watch for buddies. You've been practicing Sense heading and Forage, haven't you?<BR>
<BR>
Level 10-11<BR>
________________________<BR>
Interesting thing happened to me at these levels. I grouped. Yes, it's a terrifying thought for a druid, but it wasn't bad at the time. If you do happen to group with another person or two, the best options are the chessboard (ask for directions) or the bandit camp. If you have three you have the option of going to the Lesser Faydark and camping the Nybright sisters. Really not worth the travelling though. I spent a good deal of time in these levels with a partner. He was a dwarf cleric, and by means of fear and cleric buffs, camping became much easier. I recommend getting a partner and camping the bandits next to the altar in BB (approx -634, -651). Harmony them all and then pull one at a time. After they've all been killed once, they'll spawn in the order you slaughtered them, so you shouldn't have to harmony again.<BR>
<BR>
Level 12-13<BR>
________________________<BR>
Same routine, just do it by yourself. Just make sure you pull far enough from the camp that if another one spawns during the fight, he/she won't come and help. You can take them apart one at a time, but two bandits on you can make things very difficult. Believe it or not, they will get you to 14; it just takes a great deal of patience.<BR>
<BR>
Level 14<BR>
________________________<BR>
I suggest at this point that you prepare a speech for the people of the Greater Faydark and Butcherblock Mountains, for level fourteen is without doubt one of the finest hours of a druid's life. You had not begun to live until now. That's right, you have them now. SoW and Bind, the pedestals upon which your future career will hinge.<BR>
<BR>
First thing, sell SoW and Bind in the Greater Faydark. Practice. You need to get faily capable at getting people to pay. One thing I cannot emphasize enough: NEVER give SoW away for free or Bind for free. Many many people disagree with this philosophy, and I suspect that if you try to make even the most remote profit, someone will try and take your business simply to spite you. The Faydark is not the best place to market simply because of the abundance of other druids, but you worked hard to get to 14, so make it pay off, even if you have to wait a while for the other druids, rangers, or shamans to clear out. Some people charge a set rate while others ask for donations. Whatever you do, though, be advised to require people to pay up front. This gives you a chance to see what they're offering. If someone's only willing to give 3 copper pieces for SoW, cancel the trade and tell him to make a better offer. Never SoW on faith, and never walk across a zone to bind someone without a guarantee. And be prepared to deal with other classes badmouthing you; if they wanted SoW to be free, they should have chosen a class that had it. Also, resist the urge to go anonymous. When travelling, if someone is willing to travel across zone for SoW, see to it that they pay considerably; people are more inclined to pay higher for it if they already have the time invested in the walk to you.<BR>
<BR>
But enough about that.<BR>
<BR>
Now you can really travel. Head to Kaladim and go left from the gates down the path to the dock. Get on a boat to Freeport and bind yourself. You have the option from there of going to the Desert of Ro or the Commons. I chose West Commons on account of the bears, but Ro leads to Oasis, which is an excellent hunting ground if you have a keen eye for lurking killers (such as Sand Giants). Wherever you go, practice kiting. Snare the mob, nuke or DoT, then switch (if you nuked, DoT; if you DoT'ed, nuke). When it gets close, turn and run, turn back and continue until it's dead. Best method is to make a general circle around where you started. If you involve a large area you'll start a train or at least get yourself killed by whatever you cross. Once you have the hang of it, your options expand dramatically. I chose to go to Qeynos. You can do this without teleporting. Ask directions if you need help. The general zone order if you travel the way I did is West Commons, Kithicor Forest, Rivervale, Misty Thicket, Runnyeye Citadel, Gorge of King Xorbb, East Karana, North Karana, West Karana, Qeynos Hills. If you do this, keep levitate, SoW, and camo on all the time. Some of those zones will get you cut down in a second if you're not careful. There are other ways to go, though.<BR>
<BR>
Level 14-19<BR>
________________________<BR>
Once you hit West Karana, head to the Qeynos Hills zone and take a right before the valley starts. You'll cross a small village with a young woman standing in front of one of the houses by the name of Misty Storyswapper (yes, that's her real name). She will take you to 19 with some diligence. Kite, med, repeat. She also loots a mandolin worth around 1 platinum. If you get bored with her (you will, trust me), head over to NK and hunt pincer beetles at around level 16 or 17. They'll be blue or even high green most of the time, but they rarely make contact during melee, so they're excellent to practice combat skills. Make sure you're relatively proficient in both 1 hand blunt and 1 hand slashing. You may not need both all the time, but the druid epic weapon is a scimitar, and the best selection of mid level weapons available are blunt. You can also experiment with charming griffawns at these levels, but it becomes very frustrating when your pet turns on you, you're out of mana, and the guards go chasing after a snake just when you need them. Also, Forage should be raising now. By 17, it should be in the mid 60's or higher at the very least.<BR>
<BR>
That puts me up to date. I hope the guide has been helpful. I'll keep my notes up to date, and if I get fair reviews from the critics at large, I'll add follow ups as the spirit moves me. If you ever need anything (not money, items, power-leveling, or buffs, but almost anything else), just let me know.<BR>
<BR>
Demoree<BR>
17th Druid at Innoruuk
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
